Pakistanis are as terrified of terrorism as anyone else in the world, remarked Bollywood actress Kalki Koechlin.
The actress, who has starred in Dev D, was speaking about her experience of shooting a documentary in Pakistan at the India Today Conclave 2017, which is being held in Grand Hyatt in Mumbai.
Speaking about the documentary Azmaish, directed by Pakistani filmmaker Sabiha Sumar, she remarked that she took the project because of her neutrality on the Pakistan-India issue. &nbsp;
Further she stated, &ldquo;From my point of view, I accepted the project out of curiosity. I had never been to Pakistan and I only knew India and Pakistan in terms of conflicts. I wanted to see another aspect, perhaps, a more human aspect,&rdquo; reports Indian media. 
Speaking about her experience in Pakistan, Kalki said &ldquo;A lot of things surprised me. One thing that I loved was their curiosity because there&rsquo;s very little outside influence in Pakistan vis-a-vis India. The openness with which they met me was very surprising.&rdquo;
She remarked that the documentary focuses on the everyday struggles of the people on both sides of the border
Cricket and Bollywood are the two things that unite India and Pakistan, she remarked. "Bollywood is huge in Pakistan. People recognised me because of&nbsp;Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani.&nbsp;Even with India, a lot of us are unified because of movies. People of northeast India speak Hindi because of Bollywood.&rdquo;

LAHORE: Former Pakistan captain Muhammad Hafeez said that the time period after his injury was difficult for him.
&ldquo;When I was injured in England I refused to play in the team. After my knee injury healed I got back in the team,&rdquo; he said, adding that making a comeback is not easy for any cricketer.
The batsman admitted that his performance in the Pakistan Super League was not satisfactory, however he said he was satisfied by his performance in Australia.
He said that in the PSL he struggled with his batting initially and twice was knocked out on zero.
He said that for the West Indies series the selectors expressed faith in him and he hoped that he performs well.
Hafeez said that he wanted to play for Pakistan honourably, and any cricketer who brings dishonour to the country should not be forgiven. "It is unfortunate that the team has found itself in the middle of a scandal once again."
Hafeez had sustained a bad case of knee injury during World T20 in March 2016&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
He had returned to cricket some months later but had got injured again halfway through Pakistan tour to England in summer of 2016&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
He had also been suspended from bowling in July 2015 after his action was reported. But his bowling action was cleared in November 2016 and he was allowed to bowl again.
